4️⃣ HTTP vs WebSocket
Evolution of Pain
Nightmare Scenario: Chat Using Only HTTP

Imagine building a chat app like WhatsApp or Slack using only HTTP.

HTTP works like this:

Client → Request → Server
Server → Response → Connection closed

4

Example:

GET /messages


Server:

200 OK

The Problem

A chat app needs instant updates.

But HTTP cannot push data to the client.

So the client must keep asking:

Client → Any new messages?
Server → No

Client → Any new messages?
Server → No

Client → Any new messages?
Server → Yes


This wastes:

Problem	Result
Many useless requests	Server overload
Network waste	Poor scalability
Delay	Messages not instant

This led to Polling.

2️⃣ Polling → Long Polling → WebSocket
Polling

Client repeatedly checks server.

Client → GET /messages (every 2 sec)

4

Problem:

Thousands of useless requests

Long Polling

Server keeps request open until data arrives.

Client → Request
Server → waits
Server → sends response when message arrives

4

Better, but still:

connection resets frequently

still HTTP overhead

3️⃣ The Cure: WebSocket

WebSocket creates a persistent connection.

Instead of opening a new connection every request.

Client ↔ Server
Client ↔ Server
Client ↔ Server

4

After the connection opens:

Both sides can send data anytime


Example chat flow:

User A → message → Server
Server → push → User B


No polling required.

4️⃣ Core Mechanism (Feynman Explanation)

Think of HTTP like email.

Send email
Wait for reply
Conversation ends


Think of WebSocket like a phone call.

Call starts
Both people talk freely
Call stays open


That is the key difference.

5️⃣ What If Sandbox (Trade-offs)
❓ What if chat used only HTTP polling?

Server would receive millions of useless requests.

Example:

1M users
Polling every 2 sec
= 500k requests/sec


Server meltdown.

❓ What if WebSocket connection drops?

Client must reconnect.

Systems usually implement:

Auto reconnect
Heartbeat ping/pong

❓ What if WebSocket used for simple APIs?

Bad idea.

Because:

connections stay open

consumes memory

unnecessary complexity

So REST APIs still use HTTP.

